Dec 4 2025

Asked Google Gemini LRM and got the following response which seems to be very solid?

How can I use GitHub to build and update resume pdf daily from a quarto markdown stored on github? The file is served up by github pages and apepars at https://jeffreyracine.github.io/vitae/vitae.pdf

The most effective way to build and update your resume PDF daily using GitHub is by implementing a GitHub Actions workflow with a scheduled cron job.

This approach automates the entire rendering process, ensuring your vitae.pdf is rebuilt from your Quarto Markdown file (.qmd) every day, even if you don't manually push a change.

Here are the steps and the required workflow file:

1. Create the GitHub Action Workflow
Create a new directory named .github/workflows/ in the root of your repository. Inside this directory, create a new YAML file, for example, daily_vitae_update.yml.

daily_vitae_update.yml
Copy the following code into the file. This workflow performs the daily rendering of your Quarto file and commits the resulting PDF.

YAML
name: Daily Quarto PDF Update

on:
  # 1. Schedule a daily run (e.g., at 04:00 UTC)
  schedule:
    - cron: '0 4 * * *'
  # 2. Allow manual triggering from the Actions tab
  workflow_dispatch:

jobs:
  build-pdf:
    # Set permissions to allow the action to write/commit files
    permissions:
      contents: write
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - name: Checkout Repository
        # Fetches the code, including history, needed for the commit step
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Set up Quarto and TinyTeX
        # TinyTeX is necessary for rendering Quarto documents to PDF
        uses: quarto-dev/quarto-actions/setup@v2
        with:
          tinytex: true
          
      - name: Render Quarto Document to PDF
        # Replace 'vitae.qmd' with the actual name of your main Quarto file
        run: quarto render vitae.qmd 

      - name: Commit and Push Updated PDF
        run: |
          # Configure Git user for the automated commit
          git config user.name "github-actions[bot]"
          git config user.email "github-actions[bot]@users.noreply.github.com"
          
          # Add the generated PDF file. The path must match where Quarto outputs the file.
          # For a single document, it usually appears in the same directory.
          git add vitae.pdf
          
          # Commit the changes. '|| true' or '|| echo' prevents the action from failing 
          # if there are no changes to the PDF (e.g., if the data didn't update).
          git commit -m "Automated daily resume update" || echo "No changes to commit"

          # Push the commit back to the main branch
          git push
2. Configure Your Repository Settings
For the daily update to work, the GitHub Action needs permission to commit and push the newly rendered PDF back into your repository.

Navigate to your repository on GitHub.

Go to Settings -> Actions -> General.

Scroll down to Workflow permissions.

Ensure that "Read and write permissions" is selected.

Click Save.

This permission is crucial as it allows the default GITHUB_TOKEN to push the updated vitae.pdf file back to the branch being served by GitHub Pages.

3. Verify GitHub Pages Configuration
Confirm that your GitHub Pages settings are correctly configured to serve the PDF from the correct source:

Navigate to your repository on GitHub.

Go to Settings -> Pages.

Under Source, ensure it points to the branch (main or gh-pages) and folder (e.g., (root) or /docs) where your Quarto source file and the generated vitae.pdf reside.

The daily action will update the vitae.pdf file in this source location, and GitHub Pages will automatically serve the newest version.

This process eliminates the need for manual local rendering and pushing, fulfilling your requirement for a daily, automated PDF update.

This video provides a great visual guide on using GitHub Actions to deploy Quarto projects: Publish a Quarto project using GitHub Pages+GitHub Actions in 6 minutes (no need to render locally!).

